Convolution theorem.
The Fourier transform translates between convolution and multiplication of functions. If "f"("x") and "g"("x") are integrable functions with Fourier transforms formula_20 and formula_21 respectively, then the Fourier transform of the convolution is given by the product of the Fourier transforms formula_20 and formula_21 (under other conventions for the definition of the Fourier transform a constant factor may appear).
