In linear time invariant (LTI) system theory, it is common to interpret "g"("x") as the impulse response of an LTI system with input "f"("x") and output "h"("x"), since substituting the unit impulse for "f"("x") yields "h"("x") = "g"("x"). In this case, formula_21 represents the frequency response of the system.
Conversely, if "f"("x") can be decomposed as the product of two square integrable functions "p"("x") and "q"("x"), then the Fourier transform of "f"("x") is given by the convolution of the respective Fourier transforms formula_113 and formula_114.
